<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-12-17T07:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-12-17T07:00:00-05:00" n="154" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d154">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A15A5/590: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Chairman of the American Delegation</hi>
                                (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Davis</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-12-17T12:00:00+00:00">December
                                    17, 1935—12 p.m.</date>
                                <lb/> [Received December 17—6:50 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>24. I am officially denying a United Press report to the effect that at
                            today’s bilateral conversations between the Japanese and ourselves,
                                Nagano<note n="7" xml:id="d154fn7">Admiral Osami Nagano, Japanese
                                delegate to the Naval Conference.</note> stated that Japan was bound
                            to reject a horizontal 20% reduction in naval strength because of the
                            popular apprehension prevailing in Japan regarding the possibility of a
                            United States attack.</p>
                        <p>Nagai<note n="8" xml:id="d154fn8">Matsuzo Nagai, Japanese Ambassador in
                                the United Kingdom and delegate to the Naval Conference.</note> told
                            me that the Japanese delegation would do likewise.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Davis</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                </body></text></TEI>